  "answer": "The forbidden case asserts a contractual-legal model for Hittite kingship, but this characterization is a modern scholarly construct, not a refutation of the cosmic-ritual dimension. The target's mechanism does not require that cosmic-ritual legitimation was the exclusive or even dominant formal ideology; it requires only that the institution depended upon it sufficiently that a perceived ritual failure—triggered by an eclipse and environmental stress—could delegitimize the king in the eyes of competing elites. Hittite royal inscriptions, prayers, and festival texts (e.g., the Plague Prayers of Muršili II, the instructions for royal funerary rituals, and the role of the king as chief priest of the Sun Goddess of Arinna) amply demonstrate that the Labarna's authority was ritually enacted and cosmically sanctioned, even if a parallel contractual-legal discourse also existed. The forbidden case thus presents a false dichotomy: the presence of contractual elements does not negate the simultaneous operation of cosmic-ritual legitimation, and the target's mechanism only requires the latter to have been operative and vulnerable to disruption, not that it was the sole ideological register."
